@node "Reason" "The motive behind Sample-X"
@{fg shine}Arp@{fg text} is a simple MIDI tool which arpeggiates incoming notes.

I was inspired to write this program by Future Music Magazine, a publication
dedicated to creating music on new technology hardware. Anyway, I heard some
sample arpeggios on the cover CD and I fell in love with the sounds almost
instantly. I wanted to produce the same thing on my own equipment but neither
my Yamaha TG300 nor Novation BassStation were capable of this feature.
Therefore I had two options.

  1. Buy a hardware arpeggiator

  OR

  2. Code one in software on my Amiga


I went for the cheaper option :-). Besides it also means that I can share this
wonderful tool with you.

Happy riffing!!!

Sheun Olatunbosun 26-11-96
@endnode

@node "Register" "Register"
Okay, here's the snag. You've got a demo version of @{b}Arp@{ub} and therefore the load
and save facilities are disabled. If you want an updated version then... send
@{"me" link "Author" 0} some email. That's it! There's no fee. I'm just interested in getting some
feedback from you Amiga musicians out there.
@endnode

@node "SystemReq" "System requirements"
@{fg shine}Arp@{fg text} requires @{b}Workbench 2.04+@{ub} and a @{b}MIDI interface@{ub}. You'll also need an
external controller such as a MIDI keyboard and a MIDI instrument. Any tone
generator or synth will do, although you'll get more mileage out of one which
is velocity sensitive. If you only have a MIDI synth with a built in keyboard
then you need to turn off the LOCAL ON feature (consult your keyboard manual).
This will instruct the synthesizer not to respond to key notes coming directly
from the keyboard. Instead, MIDI notes leave the keyboard, get mangled
(arpeggiated) by the Amiga and are then sent back to the sound section of your
MIDI synth. Voila, you'll hear the arpeggio correctly.


The @{b}midi.library@{ub} is also required.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@{b}Arp@{ub} has the following features


   - Simple delay unit
   - up to 24 note arpeggio
   - MIDI keyboard / mouse arpeggio input
   - Any style pattern (ascending, descending, random)
   - Fixed / freestyle mode
   - Bypass facility
   - Selectable MIDI channels
   - Suspend mode
   - On-line guidance
   - Load/save settings (not in demo version)

NEW

   - Reconfigurable MIDI ports
   - 0% reduction for infinite looping
@endnode

@node "GetStart" "Getting Started"
You can start@{b} Arp@{ub} from the CLI by entering 'Arp' or double click on its icon
from Workbench. Arp will then attempt to open on an available public screen,
This is will typically be the Workbench screen. You are greeted with two
windows entitled 'Panel' and 'Configure'.

With your MIDI equipment attached try playing a few notes... you should hear a
wonderful bouncing riff which fades away. Now all you have to do is play
around with the parameters on the following windows

  @{" Panel     " link "WPanel" 0} - set the timing of the arpeggio/delay unit
  @{" Configure " link "WConfigure" 0} - input arpeggio pattern
  @{" Channels  " link "WChanarp" 0} - choose which channels will be arpeggiated
@endnode

@node "ScreenL" "The appearance of Arp"
  @{b}Menu@{ub}

  Shortcuts for menu options are shown in parentheses. Therefore (@{b}A@{ub} + C)
  stands for Right Amiga key + A key to open/close the Configure window.

  @{" Project     " link "MProject" 0}
  @{" Windows     " link "MWindows" 0}

  @{b}Windows@{ub}

  @{" Panel             " link "WPanel" 0}
  @{" Configure         " link "WConfigure" 0}
  @{" MIDI channels     " link "WChanarp" 0}
  @{" Suspend           " link "WSuspend" 0}
@endnode

@node "MProject" "Project menustrip"
 @{b}Load Setting@{ub}   (@{b}A@{ub} + S)
 Load a preconfigured arpeggio pattern@{i} (not available in demo version)@{ui}

 @{b}Save Setting@{ub}   (@{b}A@{ub} + L)
 Save a preconfigured arpeggio pattern @{i}(not available in demo version)@{ui}

 @{b}Suspend@{ub}        (@{b}A@{ub} + X)
 Cause Arp to enter @{"suspend mode" link "WSuspend" 0}.

 @{b}About@{ub}          (@{b}A@{ub} + A)
 Gives information about the current version and author of Arp.

 @{b}Quit@{ub}           (@{b}A@{ub} + Q)
 A pop-up requester will ask for confirmation of the action to quit and then
 Arp will close.
@endnode

@node "MWindows" "What the windows mean"
This menu strip allows you to open the two windows

                 (shortcut)

 @{"Configure " link "WConfigure" 0}      (A + C)
 @{"Channels  " link "WChanarp" 0}      (A + M)

The last menu item determines where MIDI input should be indicated by a
flashing box appearing around the title Arpeggiator on the Panel window.
@endnode

@node "WPanel" "Panel"
The @{b}Panel@{ub} window gives access to changing the timing and looping of the
current arpeggio.

@{b}Bypass@{ub}

This option allows you to bypass the arpeggio facility. It's as if the
external MIDI keyboard were routed directly to your synth without going
through the computer.@{b}

Delay@{ub}

The delay parameter specifies the time interval (in milliseconds) between
notes played in an arpeggio sequence. The short the delay the quicker the
arpgeggio.

 Too short delays or many arpeggio notes may cause hanging.

@{b}Feedback@{ub}

This option allows the @{i}output@{ui} from the delay unit to be fed back to the @{i}input@{ui}
of the delay unit. The result is an arpeggio which fades with volume (well
really note velocity) over time. NOTE: the feedback effect in freestyle mode
can only be heard when the notes on the external keyboard are held down. Hint:
an arpeggio of just one note causes Arp to act as a delay unit in fixed mode.

@{b}Reduction@{ub}

This value specifies by how much the delayed and fedback notes should be
reduced. A reduction of 50% would cause a note struck with initial velocity of
64 would later be played by Arp at velocities of 32, 16, 8 and so on

@{b}Freestyle@{ub}

Turn on the @{"freestyle mode" link "Freestyle" 0}. If this not selected then Arp is playing in @{"fixed" link "Fixed" 0}
@{"mode" link "Fixed" 0}.

@{b}N Length@{ub}

Because notes are held down in freestyle arpeggio mode, it's not possible to
determine how long each note in the sequence should be. Therefore the note
length specifies the duration of each note to be a percentage of the delay
time. Therefore for a delay of 200ms and a note length of 50%, each note will
have a duration of 100ms.

@{b}Status Panel@{ub}

The text box at the bottom of the window provides help information about the
current state of Arp.

@{b}Stop@{ub}

Hit this button if there are any hung notes. It will stop all notes currently
playing.

@{b}Input port@{ub} Specifies the name of the port from which Arp reads its MIDI data.
Instead of the serial port, it could be the output from another program such
as @{"Vect-X" link "Vect-X" 0}.

@{b}Output port@{ub} Specifies the name of the port to which Arp sends its MIDI data.
Instead of the serial port, it could send the output to another program such
as Vect-X. This would allow combined arpeggio and vector synthesis action on t
he Amiga.
@endnode

@node "WConfigure" "Configure window"
The @{b}Configure@{ub} window is where you specify an arpeggio pattern. It is used to
configure the arpeggio for both the @{"fixed mode" link "Fixed" 0} and @{"freestyle mode" link "Freestyle" 0}.

@{b}Config@{ub}

This button allows a new arpeggio pattern to be entered. The screen keyboard
is cleared of the old arpeggio setting. You have the choice of entering notes
via a mouse by clicking on screen keyboard or via an external MIDI keyboard.
Each pair of octaves on an external keyboard is mapped to the two octaves on
screen. This action happens only during configuration. As you enter notes the
selected one will be marked with a blue square. Furthermore, note information
appears in the text box below the keyboard. The information shows the arpeggio
sequence which is specified as an element (the number in parentheses) followed
by a note offset. The middle C on the screen keyboard corresponds to a note
offset of 0. The leftmost C corresponds to a note offset of -12 and rightmost
B to +11. So for example, a display of (1)0 (2)7 means that @{b}Arp@{ub} will play a
note (offset 0) and then the note 7 semitones up (offset 7).

Up to a maximum of 24 notes can be specified in the sequence.

NOTE: no arpeggio is heard while entering a new one.

@{b}Set@{ub}

Once the sequence is entered, the user selects this button to inform Arp of
his new arpeggio.

@{b}Undo@{ub}

This button can be selected any time after the Config or Set action to ignore
entry of a new arpegio sequence, and thus revert back to the old entry.

@{b}Arrow buttons  If the user enters a very long arpeggio thn it is not possible
to see all of it at once. Use the arrow buttons to scroll through the whole
display of the arpeggio.

@{i}This window can be closed by the close gadget in the top left or the keyboard
combination of Right Amiga + C.@{ui}
@endnode

@node "WChanarp" "Enabling MIDI channel arpeggiation "
The @{b}Channels@{ub} window makes it possible to enable the arpeggio facility for just
a certain number of the sixteen MIDI channels.

To the left of window is a strip containing the numbers 1 to 16. Whenever a
number is selected with the mouse, its adjacent box is toggled between on
(white) and off (grey). The on/off status indicates whether the arpeggio is
working for that MIDI channel.

To disable the arpeggio facility for all sixteen channels, there is the @{"Bypass" link "WPanel" 0}
button available from the @{b}Panel@{ub} window.

@{i}The Channels window can be closed by the close gadget to the top left of the
window or the keyboard combination Right Amiga + M.@{ui}
@endnode

@node "Fixed" "fixed mode arpeggiator"
@{b}FIXED MODE@{ub}

Arp holds the information about an arpeggio in the form of an ordered sequence
of note offsets. It plays once through the sequence to achieve the arpeggio
effect.

 Example
 -------

 @{i}during configration...@{ui}

        Notes entered   mC,  G, mC,  E        @{i} mC is middle C on@{ui}
 Ordered Note offsets    0, -5,  0, +4        @{i} screen keyboard@{ui}

 With the arpeggio set, you can play it on note D of your keyboard

 Result
 ------

 @{i}after configuration...@{ui}

 Struck note             D,  D,  D,  D
 Ordered Note offsets    0, -5,  0, +4

 @{b}Arp@{ub} plays notes ---->   D,  A,  D, F#

Therefore one finger presses can produce beautiful riffs. Unfortunately the
simplicity of the mode renders it inflexible. For example, it's not possible
to play just chords (in the form of arpeggios of course) from just the C-major
scale as witnessed above. The desired arpeggio to play on striking note D
would be D, A, D, F  (or Dminor). So if you want to confine arpegggios to a
musical scale, use the @{"freestyle mode" link "Freestyle" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Freestyle" "freestyle mode arpeggiator"
@{b}FREESTYLE MODE@{ub}

This mode offers greater flexibility in terms of which notes are played in an
arpeggio. But for the arpeggio to be heard, it is necessary to HOLD DOWN the
relevant notes.

 Example
 -------

 @{i}during configuration...@{ui}

         Notes entered  mC,  G, mC,  E           @{i}mC is middle C on@{ui}
         Note offsets    0, -5,  0, +4           @{i}screen keyboard@{ui}

 Ordered Note sequence   G,  C,  E              @{i}number of unique notes = 3@{ui}
                 index   1,  2,  3

 Arpeggio note
               (index)-> @{fg shine}2,  1,  2,  3@{fg text}


In freestyle mode, Arp pays attention only to the sequence of entered notes.
For the above example, it states that for any chord composed of up to three
notes, play the middle note (2), then the lowest note (1) then the middle note
(2) followed by the highest note(3) to get the arpeggio. So some examples are
shown below.

 Chord notes             Index        Arpeggio sequence    Note offsets

 G, B, D (G-Major)       1, 2, 3      B, G, B, D           4, 0, 4, 7  (G=0)
 A, C, E (A-minor)       1, 2, 3      C, A, C, E           3, 0, 3, 7  (A=0)
 C, F, A (F-major        1, 2, 3      F, C, F, A           5, 0, 5, 9  (C=0)
         1st inversion)

Notice how the note offsets are different for each chord, but the desired
sequence of correct notes in the arpeggio is maintained. For the example
arpeggio entered, you could hold down fewer than 3 keys with the result being
that some parts of the arpeggio will be missed. Holding down more than three
keys will cause some notes not to be heard since the entered arpeggio was only
configured for three unique notes.


 For the given arpeggio sequence@{fg shine} 2,1,2,3@{fg text}

 Held chord notes    Index      Arp plays...

 G                   1          . G . .             . = nothing
 G D                 1 2        D G D .
 D G                 1 2        G D G .
 G B D F             1 2 3 4    B G B D



Okay, if none of the above is understood, then I STRONGLY suggest you
experiment with Arp to see what it's doing. That will be half the fun of it
anyway.
@endnode

@node "WSuspend" "Suspend window"
The @{b}Suspend@{ub} window pops up following the selection of the Suspend option from
the @{"Project" link "MProject" 0} menu strip. All MIDI activity ceases and the Arp GUI becomes
disabled. This suspend mode is also mentioned in the @{"status" link "WPanel" 0} panel. During this
time, the serial port is freed so that other programs may use it.

To resume normal operation of @{b}Arp@{ub}, click on the button marked @{i}Restart Arp@{ui}. If
everything is okay then Arp will become operational again. However if there is
a problem, such as the serial port being unavailable, then a requester will
appear. The user has the option of trying to obtain the serial port again or
leaving the program.
@endnode

@node "Glossary" "Glossary"
Some important terms appearing in documentation.

@{b}Arpeggio@{ub}

The action of playing in sequence the individual notes of a chord. This is
different from normal chord action where all the notes are played
simultaneously. Therefore instead of playing a C major chord as C E G together
it is played as C then E then G, or maybe E then G then C. In fact the
arpgeggio can be the chordal notes played in any order.

@{b}Fixed arpeggio @{ub}

The one finger action used in @{b}Arp@{ub} to play arpeggios. Its simplicity means that
note offsets are the same for whatever key is struck. Consequently it is
possible to play non-scalar (or disharmonious) note sequences.

@{b}Freestyle arpeggio @{ub}

The multi-finger action used in @{b}Arp@{ub} to play arpeggios. Arp cycles amongst the
notes specified by the user so that is possible to always play harmonious
arpeggios.


@{b}MIDI@{ub}

Musical Instrument Digital Interface. A protocol used between hardware units
for the transfer of notes and other messages relating to musical information.


@{b}MIDI channel@{ub}

This is one of the sixteen lines on which notes can be transmitted. Each line
has a note span of 128 notes or different pitches and each one has its own
parameters such as volume, panning and pitch-bend. This permits an arrangement
where each channel can trigger a different musical instrument.
@endnode

